        heading: "How Google Tests Mobile-Friendliness: Evaluation Criteria",
        body: "Google mobile-friendly test checks five primary criteria. First viewport configuration - pages need meta name viewport content width=device-width initial-scale=1 tag telling mobile browsers to render at actual device width. Second font size - body text must be readable without zooming. Minimum recommended font size is 16px CSS pixels. Text under 14px is flagged too small. Third tap target size - interactive elements should be at least 48x48 CSS pixels with 8px spacing between targets preventing fat finger errors. Fourth content width - page should not require horizontal scrolling. Content must fit within viewport width. Fifth flash usage - page must not use Flash content unsupported on mobile. Beyond these checks Google also evaluates mobile page speed as part of mobile user experience assessment. The Toolverse mobile-friendly test tool checks all criteria with detailed results per issue including specific URL and element causing the problem. The Toolverse page speed checker complements this by measuring real mobile performance metrics."
